<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910522-0066</DOCNO><DOCID>910522-0066.</DOCID><HL>   Law:   Plea in Business Week Case   Brings 3 Years' Probation</HL><DATE>05/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   MHP</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)SECURITIES REGULATIONS AND ENFORCEMENT (RGU)SECURITIES (SCR)</IN><NS>SECURITIES REGULATION (RGU)</NS><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)</GV><RE>NEW YORK (NY)</RE><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- A former stockbroker who pleaded guilty toprofiting from advance knowledge of a Business Week magazinestock column was sentenced to three years' probation by afederal judge.   Lawrence Small, a resident of the Pacific Palisades area,also was ordered to perform 400 hours of community service byU.S. District Judge Terry Hatter. Mr. Small was not fined bythe court, but has agreed to disgorge about $57,000 inprofits in an agreement with the Securities and ExchangeCommission, said Stanley S. Arkin, Mr. Small's lawyer.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Small pleaded guilty in January to two counts ofinsider trading. According to a government suit, Mr. Smallmade the profits between September 1986 and July 1988 usingthe advance information from the column. He faced a maximumsentence of 10 years in prison and as much as $500,000 infines. Three other defendants have pleaded guilty in thecase.</TEXT></DOC>